text_Original:
Honestly, the biggest and only use case for this product is to help people like the late Stephen Hawking speak and make presentations if AI could interpret him live from his wheelchair.

Synthesize expression, facial muscles, age, voice, and composite sentences based on his past writing and active inputs even if it's only a blink. The most we could get from this is enabling the disabled - which is huge, dont Get me wrong. But it's not even going to come close to breaking even seeing as how we disabled people aren't generally the richest or most productive to have barter chips to trade for the cost of developing this product.

It's a really neat toy, a really niche tool, but the demand won't be able to afford it for its best use cases and the wealthy who can afford will get bored of it almost immediately because they just don't need or want to use it for anything.

text_Original:
The main point is that when you dream you can have feelings and sensations without the sense-presentation objects...

"02:55 a.m. I had a dream and woke up. Let's talk about dream, sensations, mind and brain. About one hour ago I wake up. The sensation was so real, as probably you already also had, because it is common the persons say: "I had a dream where things appears to be real". Let's observes this fact with a question. Do I need previously feel the reality to have a dream about this specific reality? Without experience of sense-presentation, can I have the supposed sensation for that situation? Let's go to examples. A person that do not had sex in reality can have an orgasm dreaming? I mean a person that never had sex before; this person can dream with a real orgasm? It is not the case of my dream. Let's proceed with one of the main pictures of my dream that probably have a direct connection with shame..."...complete article (About the dream activity and initial questions for a new machine) here: https://rdc.pro.br/world/evolution/
